    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Darwin in Kansas</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lisa Stillman letter comments on August 3 article on repuidiation by Kansas voters of state school board's removal of human evolution from state's science standards (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Evolution Foes Dealt a Defeat in Kansas Vote'' (front page, Aug. 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Evolution Foes Dealt a Defeat in Kansas Vote'' (front page, Aug. 3):</p>
        <p>Instead of being defensive, evolutionists who care about the education of young people should welcome opposing views into the classroom. Science, after all, is about questioning authority and about deciding what kind of evidence constitutes proof.</p>
        <p>Charles Darwin spent years gathering evidence for evolution before presenting his ideas to the public. Why should we expect -- or even want -- high school students to accept scientific dogma?</p>
        <p>Even if they're taught the ''correct'' theories, they will forever lack the intellectual tools to distinguish for themselves between good science and hogwash.</p>
        <p>LISA STILLMAN  New York, Aug. 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
